profile_89304_qwen3:30b.think_process: Politics in Uruguay have been a constant backdrop to my life, from the dictatorship era to the democratic governments I've lived through. As someone with a postgraduate degree and a comfortable life in Montevideo, I've always believed in civic duty—voting, reading the paper, knowing where my money goes. But after 62 years, I've seen enough broken promises and empty rhetoric to know that getting caught up in every election cycle is exhausting. I follow the main issues that actually affect my daily life—like healthcare costs for my pension or school fees for my grandchildren—but I don't need to dissect every political debate over coffee. My friends and I talk about it casually, but we don't lose sleep over it. I vote because it's important, but I don't feel I need to be "very interested" in the whirlwind of campaigns and scandals. "Somewhat interested" feels right—I'm engaged enough to stay informed on the essentials, but not so much that it consumes me. After all, I have a garden to tend and my grandchildren to watch.
